## 3. Narration Toggle Infrastructure

A narration system provides hooks for future screen reader integration:

```rust
#[derive(Default, Clone)]
struct AccessibilitySettings {
    palette: ColorPaletteMode,
    narration_enabled: bool,
}

fn toggle_narration(&mut self, cx: &mut Context<Self>) {
    self.accessibility.narration_enabled = !self.accessibility.narration_enabled;
    if self.accessibility.narration_enabled {
        info!("Narration enabled");
    } else {
        info!("Narration disabled");
    }
    cx.notify();
}
```

When enabled, the system will (in future implementation) emit narration events:

```rust
// Future narration event emission
if self.accessibility.narration_enabled {
    match event {
        SimulationEvent::AgentBirth { id, position } => {
            narrate(format!("New agent spawned at {}, {}", position.x, position.y));
        }
        SimulationEvent::AgentDeath { id, cause } => {
            narrate(format!("Agent died from {}", cause));
        }
        SimulationEvent::Combat { attacker, victim, damage } => {
            narrate(format!("Agent {} attacked agent {} for {} damage", attacker, victim, damage));
        }
        // ...
    }
}
```

These narration hooks will integrate with:
- **macOS**: VoiceOver API
- **Windows**: SAPI or Narrator API
- **Linux**: Speech Dispatcher

The narration system will provide audio feedback for:
- Population milestones (first birth, 100 agents, etc.)
- Significant events (first carnivore kill, extinction, etc.)
- User actions (palette changed, playback paused, etc.)
- Performance warnings (FPS dropped below 30, memory pressure, etc.)

### Narration UI

The toggle appears in the accessibility panel:

```rust
let narration_button = {
    let listener = cx.listener(|this, _, _, cx| {
        this.toggle_narration(cx);
    });

    let base = div()
        .rounded_md()
        .border_1()
        .px_2()
        .py_1()
        .text_xs()
        .child(if self.accessibility.narration_enabled {
            "Narration: On"
        } else {
            "Narration: Off"
        })
        .on_mouse_down(MouseButton::Left, listener);

    if self.accessibility.narration_enabled {
        base.border_color(rgb(0x38bdf8))
            .bg(rgb(0x1e3a8a))
            .text_color(rgb(0xe0f2fe))
    } else {
        base.border_color(rgb(0x1e293b))
            .bg(rgb(0x111b2b))
            .text_color(rgb(0xcbd5f5))
    }
};
```

The button provides clear visual feedback of the narration state, styled consistently
with other accessibility controls.

## 4. Core Reproduction Pipeline Cleanup

Several code simplifications improve the reproduction system:

### Removed Unused Helpers

```rust
// Removed: unused helper that was superseded by inline implementation
fn log_mutation(log: &mut Vec<String>, label: &str, before: f32, after: f32) {
    if (after - before).abs() > 1e-4 {
        log.push(format!("{label}:{before:.3}->{after:.3}"));
    }
}

// Removed: method now inlined at call site for clarity
fn species_reproduction_rate(&self, herbivore_factor: f32) -> f32 {
    let h = herbivore_factor.clamp(0.0, 1.0);
    let carn = self.config.reproduction_rate_carnivore;
    carn + (self.config.reproduction_rate_herbivore - carn) * h
}
```

These methods were abstracted prematurely when only used in one location. Inlining improves
code readability by keeping the logic at the call site.

### Inlined Reproduction Rate Calculation

```rust
// Before:
let reproduction_rate = self.species_reproduction_rate(runtime.herbivore_tendency);

// After:
let rate_carnivore = self.config.reproduction_rate_carnivore;
let rate_herbivore = self.config.reproduction_rate_herbivore;
let herb = runtime.herbivore_tendency.clamp(0.0, 1.0);
let reproduction_rate = rate_carnivore + (rate_herbivore - rate_carnivore) * herb;
```

This makes the interpolation formula explicit at the call site, clarifying that herbivores
and carnivores have different base rates that blend based on `herbivore_tendency`.

### Removed Verbose Gene Log Entry

```rust
// Removed:
child_runtime.push_gene_log(
    gene_log_capacity,
    format!(
        "spawn parent={:?} partner={} rate={:.2}",
        agent_id,
        partner_index
            .map(|j| format!("{:?}", handles[j]))
            .unwrap_or_else(|| "none".to_string()),
        self.species_reproduction_rate(parent_runtime_snapshot.herbivore_tendency)
    ),
);
```

This log entry was excessively verbose, cluttering the gene log with spawn metadata that's
already captured in the lineage field. Removing it keeps gene logs focused on trait mutations.

### Clippy Lint Allowance

```rust
#[allow(clippy::too_many_arguments)]
fn build_child_data(
    &mut self,
    parent: &AgentData,
    parent_runtime: &AgentRuntime,
    partner_runtime: Option<&AgentRuntime>,
    rng: &mut SmallRng,
    width: f32,
    height: f32,
) -> AgentData {
    // ...
}
```

The `build_child_data` method requires many parameters to construct offspring without
global state. While refactoring into a builder pattern could reduce parameters, the
current design is clear and performant. The `#[allow]` attribute documents this intentional
design choice, preventing false-positive warnings.

## 5. Footer Enhancements

The footer now displays accessibility state:

```rust
fn render_footer(&self, snapshot: &HudSnapshot) -> Div {
    let mut lines = Vec::new();

    // ... existing footer lines

    lines.push(format!(
        "Palette {} · Narration {}",
        self.accessibility.palette.label(),
        if self.accessibility.narration_enabled {
            "ON"
        } else {
            "OFF"
        }
    ));

    if let Some(action) = self.key_capture {
        lines.push(format!("Rebinding {}...", action.label()));
    }

    // ...
}
```

This provides at-a-glance visibility of accessibility settings without requiring navigation
to the inspector panel, following the principle of making settings discoverable and
transparent.

## 6. Event Handling Integration

Keyboard events are now captured at the root level:

```rust
impl Render for SimulationView {
    fn render(&mut self, cx: &mut Context<Self>) -> impl IntoElement {
        // ... render elements

        div()
            .flex()
            .flex_col()
            .child(canvas_container)
            .child(footer)
            .on_key_down(cx.listener(|this, event: &KeyDownEvent, _, cx| {
                this.handle_key_down(event, cx);
            }))
    }
}
```

This ensures keyboard input is processed consistently, supporting both command execution
and key capture mode from any focus state within the window.

